WEBVTT

00:00:00.320 --> 00:00:06.240
Awesome. Hi, I'm Ryan Timpe. I'm a data scientist at The LEGO Group. It's a really cool job. I get

00:00:06.240 --> 00:00:11.680
to combine my passion for data science with a really awesome brand. But I have to say today,

00:00:11.680 --> 00:00:17.680
I'm representing myself, not them. So got that out of the way. I'm here to talk about data science

00:00:17.680 --> 00:00:22.959
in general as in 2025. Because being a data scientist this year is a lot different than

00:00:22.959 --> 00:00:29.840
being one in 2020, or even maybe last year. And again, one of those big differences is I have AI

00:00:29.840 --> 00:00:34.400
and large language models to help me be more productive. So I know we're in day two of

00:00:34.400 --> 00:00:39.200
posit.conference. It's the afternoon, you probably have heard so much about LLMs, and it's not

00:00:39.200 --> 00:00:45.360
stopping here. But bear with me, because this talk is a little bit different. It kind of compliments

00:00:45.360 --> 00:00:49.119
the ones we've been hearing a lot. Well, because I'm talking about everything they've gotten wrong

00:00:49.119 --> 00:00:56.400
for me and how I've dealt with that. So if you use a coding assistant at all, or a chat interface,

00:00:56.400 --> 00:01:01.599
you might recognize this window. You can ask the AI some questions or respond with grandiose

00:01:01.599 --> 00:01:06.480
yes-man statements that could be super helpful for you. How many of you have looked at that

00:01:06.480 --> 00:01:14.480
fine print, though? So Gemini can make mistakes. So double check it. Or this one. Chat GPT can make

00:01:14.480 --> 00:01:20.800
mistakes. Check important information. Two really short sentences. The first one admits that the

00:01:20.800 --> 00:01:28.639
tool is flawed. And the second one encourages human collaboration. So again, I've come across

00:01:28.639 --> 00:01:33.839
so many mistakes using AI in the past year. But this talk is all about embracing those mistakes,

00:01:33.839 --> 00:01:37.680
dealing with them, overcoming them, and how that human collaboration is really important.

00:01:39.199 --> 00:01:44.080
And I've used AI professionally for a few things now, like learning new coding languages,

00:01:44.879 --> 00:01:49.919
trying out new methodologies, and replicating previous work I've done. Each one of these has

00:01:49.919 --> 00:01:57.599
come with mistakes, and I've learned a lot coming out of them. So my first professional real

00:01:57.599 --> 00:02:04.320
engagement with LLMs was learning Python. My tools and platform at work have changed, and I'm being

00:02:04.320 --> 00:02:11.759
forced to be as productive in Pandas and PySpark as I have been for years in R and SQL. And AI has

00:02:11.759 --> 00:02:18.080
been great here. I know the data science I need to do, and the AI can do the new language for me.

00:02:18.960 --> 00:02:24.240
And when I first started using AI and coding assistants to help me learn Python, things went

00:02:24.240 --> 00:02:29.839
great. Some things worked very, very well. Such as very discrete individual prompts I saw were

00:02:29.839 --> 00:02:35.440
great. I could say import this data. Yes, it knows how to do that. Transform this data or group it by

00:02:35.440 --> 00:02:41.279
and summarize. Very easy tasks from go to point A to point B. The AI was great at giving me code to

00:02:41.279 --> 00:02:47.440
do that. Really big greedy tasks worked as well. So this one built a mix effects model with this

00:02:47.440 --> 00:02:52.000
data in these three columns. That worked great. I could even say build me a shiny app. It had

00:02:52.000 --> 00:02:58.399
code to do that. It mostly worked great. The way I work is I take really small tasks, I tie them

00:02:58.399 --> 00:03:03.679
together. I import my data, I review it, I summarize it, I transpose it, and I put it into

00:03:03.679 --> 00:03:10.800
models. I do A to B, B to C, C to D, and so on forever. And when I was linking the output of my

00:03:11.360 --> 00:03:16.479
discrete from the AI and putting those all together and putting that code into different

00:03:16.479 --> 00:03:23.039
chunks of my notebook, I was getting failures all over the place. Specifically with this, I was

00:03:23.039 --> 00:03:27.919
seeing that my LLM was proposing very different approaches to answer similar prompts. I was seeing

00:03:27.919 --> 00:03:32.960
new functions pop up all the time. I was seeing new syntaxes I didn't understand. And I was also

00:03:32.960 --> 00:03:37.679
getting type errors. So my notebook seemed to be forgetting what data frames were. I was very

00:03:37.679 --> 00:03:44.240
confused. This exact problem was that my LLM in my case was swapping between PySpark and Pandas.

00:03:44.240 --> 00:03:50.160
And I had skipped all that basic Python, so I didn't know the difference. It's fine.

00:03:52.399 --> 00:03:57.279
So the LLM and I were working under very different assumptions. My environment was very much

00:03:57.279 --> 00:04:04.399
PySpark dependent, and I hadn't known that. But since I was a Tidyverse person for so long, I

00:04:04.399 --> 00:04:09.440
always said I had heard about Pandas. And so in my head, I was sometimes trying to do Pandas work,

00:04:09.440 --> 00:04:15.119
and that didn't work out. So we had a very big miscommunication between myself and the LLM.

00:04:15.839 --> 00:04:20.720
And I also had very imprecise prompts. I was letting the AI make all the decisions for me,

00:04:20.720 --> 00:04:27.440
because I wasn't telling it what to do. This is all fixable, though. So after I realized my issue,

00:04:27.440 --> 00:04:32.079
I could revisit my prompts and write better prompts and really make that point A to B,

00:04:32.079 --> 00:04:36.959
B to C process work a lot better. So now, of course, when I'm working with prompts,

00:04:36.959 --> 00:04:41.600
I'm very clear about what tools I'm using, what libraries to use. I'm very clear about my input

00:04:41.600 --> 00:04:46.239
data. If it's in the notebook, I can reference old chunks. If I'm in a chat interface, I can

00:04:46.239 --> 00:04:51.920
describe my data very well before I just ask the AI to give me solutions. And same with the output.

00:04:51.920 --> 00:04:57.279
I'm very, very clear about what output I want out of the AI. It's a little bit more effort,

00:04:57.279 --> 00:05:02.079
but it saves me so much more time and pain by just being more precise with my prompts.

00:05:02.640 --> 00:05:07.679
So at this point, for a few months, I'm producing a lot of new data science projects in Python,

00:05:07.679 --> 00:05:12.799
and I had overcome this hurdle. And I think at this point, yeah, I must be a Python data

00:05:12.799 --> 00:05:18.480
scientist by now, because I'm producing Python. It's great. So if you had asked me or if a recruiter

00:05:18.480 --> 00:05:25.760
had asked me or my boss had asked me, I'd be like, yeah, I know Python now. Yeah, because I was

00:05:26.640 --> 00:05:33.359
delivering in Python, so that counts. And so then one day I go to test myself, I open up a notebook,

00:05:33.359 --> 00:05:39.200
I import my libraries, and then nothing. My mind went blank. Turns out I did not know Python now.

00:05:40.480 --> 00:05:46.880
I was way too reliant on the AI. Nothing was retaining. It's so bad to the point,

00:05:46.880 --> 00:05:51.359
like I was still asking the AI to import my data and read my parquet file rather than me just

00:05:51.359 --> 00:06:00.000
typing the pd.read parquet. I was so lazy. So one, this is embarrassing and not good for me,

00:06:00.000 --> 00:06:04.239
and I wasn't happy with myself, but also it was really inefficient. I was spending so much time

00:06:04.239 --> 00:06:08.720
rewriting prompts and then manually editing the output of prompts that I think it would have been

00:06:08.720 --> 00:06:13.040
a lot faster for me to actually know Python and write some code. So this was another big

00:06:13.040 --> 00:06:18.959
wake-up moment for me. I had to be a lot more engaged with my code. I was doing passive reviews,

00:06:19.679 --> 00:06:24.239
okay, I see the words, everything makes sense, but now I'm a lot more active in my review.

00:06:25.440 --> 00:06:29.359
I'm studying the code that comes out of it. I make sure I know what functions are, and it's nice,

00:06:29.359 --> 00:06:32.720
because if I don't understand a function, I don't understand what they're doing, I can be like, hey,

00:06:32.720 --> 00:06:36.239
I can ask the AI coding assistant, why did you do it this way, and it's usually really good at

00:06:36.239 --> 00:06:40.880
answering that. So this was another big turning point for me. It slowed me down a little bit,

00:06:40.880 --> 00:06:44.239
but I also feel a lot more comfortable with my work, because I actually understand what I'm

00:06:44.239 --> 00:06:51.760
producing now. But it also turns out that I'm a paid data scientist, so I can't just be learning

00:06:51.760 --> 00:06:57.279
all the time. I'm expected to produce once in a while. But AI has been great here as well.

00:06:59.600 --> 00:07:04.160
So I've been at my company for quite a few years now, and so I'm working with the same

00:07:04.160 --> 00:07:08.640
stakeholders year after year, quarter after quarter. They're getting very data savvy,

00:07:08.640 --> 00:07:12.320
because they're getting used to seeing data science output, and so they're asking more

00:07:12.320 --> 00:07:16.799
exciting questions and more interesting questions. Sometimes I don't have the tools to answer those

00:07:16.799 --> 00:07:23.359
questions, and AI can do that. So for one example, I had to come up with a new type of demand model

00:07:23.359 --> 00:07:27.600
with some very specific constraints for price and substitution effect. I didn't know how to do it,

00:07:27.600 --> 00:07:31.519
but then online, I found an academic paper that showed me exactly how to do that.

00:07:32.480 --> 00:07:37.519
The problem is that academic papers are very long and very dense. I'm a business person. I don't

00:07:37.519 --> 00:07:44.160
read those. But it's fine. I turned to my AI. I was like, hey, here's this 20-page paper. You

00:07:44.160 --> 00:07:50.239
read it, and gave me the Python code to run this model. And it said sure, and it gave me trash.

00:07:51.920 --> 00:07:57.359
No surprise there. It gave me some code. I didn't understand it. I didn't know the inputs. I didn't

00:07:57.359 --> 00:08:01.440
know what it was trying to do. It was basically a nonstarter. I could not work this way.

00:08:02.000 --> 00:08:06.399
But also, I needed these models, because I was under a deadline, and I couldn't give up,

00:08:06.399 --> 00:08:13.679
and I knew AI could help. So here, I started over. I took the paper. But this time, I actually

00:08:13.679 --> 00:08:19.359
tried to read it. And I pulled out the snippets that I thought were important, but then I added

00:08:19.359 --> 00:08:24.799
a few things. So when I went to the LLM, I gave it some business context. I told the LLM, hey,

00:08:24.799 --> 00:08:29.279
this is how I need to use this paper. These are the questions I'm getting. This is the methodology

00:08:29.279 --> 00:08:34.880
I need to use. I gave it some pseudocode. The paper had some Matlab pseudocode in it. I didn't

00:08:34.880 --> 00:08:40.400
know what to do with that, but the AI could. I gave it sample data, so exactly the input data

00:08:40.400 --> 00:08:45.440
that I would be working with and what I would expect to put into the models, and also a description

00:08:45.440 --> 00:08:50.559
of the output, what I needed to come out of this. And then I fed that to my LLM, and I actually got

00:08:50.559 --> 00:08:55.520
something. It was a few hundred lines of very well-documented code. It did not work still at

00:08:55.520 --> 00:09:01.280
the first try, but I could see how it approached the problem, and this was way more informed than

00:09:01.280 --> 00:09:06.719
I could have been. So I could read the code and follow kind of what it was trying to do,

00:09:06.719 --> 00:09:10.479
but now I could read the code side by side with that original paper. This really helped me

00:09:10.479 --> 00:09:14.880
understand the paper a lot better, and then by understanding the paper better, I was able to go

00:09:14.880 --> 00:09:19.919
back to the not-working Python code, find the bugs, fix it, and actually got those models running

00:09:19.919 --> 00:09:24.880
after a few hours, and without AI, this would have taken probably quite a few days for me to do.

00:09:25.599 --> 00:09:32.080
And this was another big changing point of how I use my LLMs. So working with an LLM now is a

00:09:32.080 --> 00:09:37.599
collaboration. I remain the expert wherever possible. I know my data better than the AI.

00:09:37.599 --> 00:09:42.320
I know my business better than the AI, at least right now. I know my stakeholders better. So I

00:09:42.320 --> 00:09:47.039
need to keep that expertise every time I'm asking an LLM to do work, and then where there's knowledge

00:09:47.039 --> 00:09:52.080
gaps, I then rely on the LLM to fill in the gaps. So here it was the exact methodology,

00:09:52.080 --> 00:10:01.440
and it was the Python code. And then basically now with this kind of help, I'm producing a lot

00:10:01.440 --> 00:10:06.640
of things in Python, and I'm kind of understanding it, and I'm giving a lot of putting a lot of

00:10:06.640 --> 00:10:12.000
things out into the business way more than I was maybe a year ago, and I'm smiling and delivering

00:10:12.000 --> 00:10:16.239
it to the business. I'm super happy, but in the back of my mind, I'm panicking, like, is this any

00:10:16.239 --> 00:10:20.960
good? Like, I'm producing a lot. I'm hoping it's giving value, and people are making decisions

00:10:20.960 --> 00:10:28.799
based off of it, but I'm also wondering, can I actually trust it? And so this is a very hard

00:10:28.799 --> 00:10:33.359
question to answer, and it really depends on probably every single business case or every

00:10:33.359 --> 00:10:38.640
single use case, but I'm a data scientist. I really like asking these questions and doing

00:10:38.640 --> 00:10:47.280
training sets and testing sets, so I decided to put my LLM through a test. A few years ago in R,

00:10:47.280 --> 00:10:51.760
I made a package that takes images and turns them into Lego mosaics, so something you could

00:10:51.760 --> 00:10:57.440
build out of Lego, and I was wondering if the LLM could reproduce that, so it took me a few weeks to

00:10:57.440 --> 00:11:02.159
do. I learned a lot. It was really fun. How fast can I get an LLM to produce the same thing?

00:11:03.119 --> 00:11:09.280
So I gave it this prompt. Write me a function that takes an image and renders it as a mosaic

00:11:09.280 --> 00:11:13.599
made of Lego bricks, and to do that, I'm going to use this image of my dog, and this is Hunter.

00:11:14.479 --> 00:11:20.239
He might look like the cartoons I've been showing around. So I took the Python script that the LLM

00:11:20.239 --> 00:11:27.119
gave me, I gave it my image file, and I got, well, nothing. It didn't run the first try,

00:11:27.119 --> 00:11:31.440
but that's fine, because I'm really good at debugging LLMs at this point, or the LLM output

00:11:31.440 --> 00:11:37.280
at this point. After a few minutes, I found some bad transpose statements, and I got this.

00:11:37.760 --> 00:11:45.039
It's not great. It's not what I asked for. I can see what it's trying to do, though,

00:11:45.039 --> 00:11:51.280
and probably from the back, it looks like my dog, but there's some issues. The colors aren't real.

00:11:51.919 --> 00:11:55.520
They chose the colors based off the image, but these are not Lego colors. I can't go to the

00:11:55.520 --> 00:12:00.640
store and buy these bricks and build this, so that's a nonstarter for me. The output size was

00:12:00.640 --> 00:12:06.000
very arbitrary. The LLM chose the output size based off of the JPEG file size, which doesn't

00:12:06.000 --> 00:12:11.039
make much sense to a Lego builder. It's all one-by-one bricks, which isn't wrong, but also

00:12:11.840 --> 00:12:16.799
not fun for me to build, and very inflexible code. So I noticed that every single time I would edit

00:12:16.799 --> 00:12:20.880
the prompt, add a new feature, it had to rewrite every single thing it was giving me, because it

00:12:20.880 --> 00:12:25.599
couldn't add that new feature into the established prompt, and then that was losing all the edits I

00:12:25.599 --> 00:12:32.559
would make manually to it, and that was just very frustrating. But then after a few prompt changes,

00:12:32.559 --> 00:12:37.359
and I kept nudging it in my direction, I got this. And from the back, I think it looks like

00:12:37.359 --> 00:12:42.159
my dog. It's all Lego bricks. It's all different sized bricks. Those are colors I can buy.

00:12:42.719 --> 00:12:47.679
And here, the LLM did what I asked, and if I compare it to my R code from a few years ago,

00:12:48.719 --> 00:12:53.760
basically the same thing. A little style changes, some color algorithm differences,

00:12:53.760 --> 00:12:58.000
but I got the LLM to produce what I wanted to produce, and that's really cool, because I got

00:12:58.000 --> 00:13:02.479
that in a matter of minutes, where suppose I manually did this maybe over a few weeks of free

00:13:02.479 --> 00:13:10.400
time. So in this one case, I can trust the LLM, but it's not because the LLM gave me what I wanted

00:13:10.400 --> 00:13:15.119
the first try. Instead, it's because I was working with the LLM along the way, nudging it in the

00:13:15.119 --> 00:13:21.280
direction I wanted to go, and that's how I gained that trust. And this is a silly example of my dog

00:13:21.280 --> 00:13:26.799
and Lego bricks, but this also follows my process at work I do a lot. So I have a very

00:13:27.440 --> 00:13:32.320
tried and trusted huge code base of models in R that I'm slowly porting over to Python.

00:13:32.880 --> 00:13:36.080
That doesn't work if I just copy and paste the whole repo and say, hey,

00:13:36.080 --> 00:13:42.239
translate this. I have to still mimic how I develop that. I do small chunks, and then I'm

00:13:42.239 --> 00:13:46.239
testing those chunks along the way, making sure they're producing exactly what I expect.

00:13:46.239 --> 00:13:50.000
Tech check against the truth. I know the truth. I've been with my business a long time. I want

00:13:50.000 --> 00:13:56.799
to make sure I can trust that. And then when I'm happy with that, I move on. So all these little

00:13:56.799 --> 00:14:01.200
mistakes I've come across in the past few years, I now have this pretty solid checklist of things

00:14:01.200 --> 00:14:05.200
that I go through when I'm working with an LLM, and that has made me a lot more productive.

00:14:05.200 --> 00:14:10.000
So just kind of rehash. I write clear, precise prompts. I have to make sure that the LLM and

00:14:10.000 --> 00:14:13.039
I are working under the same assumptions, and I'm the one making those assumptions.

00:14:14.000 --> 00:14:17.840
I work in these really small increments, doing small things at a time, trusting the

00:14:17.840 --> 00:14:24.799
increments along the way. I treat the LLM as a collaborator, not a replacement. So I'm an

00:14:24.799 --> 00:14:29.679
expert in a lot of things. I have to keep that. I stay engaged. I'm the one responsible for the

00:14:29.679 --> 00:14:34.400
code I am at the end of the day. When my business stakeholders are using it, I can't blame an LLM

00:14:34.400 --> 00:14:38.559
that's wrong. It comes to me. I want to make sure I can vouch for every single line of that code,

00:14:38.559 --> 00:14:41.760
and then I can just continuously validate the output against what I know to be true.

00:14:42.719 --> 00:14:46.400
So going back to my initial statement, how data science is different this year,

00:14:46.400 --> 00:14:50.400
yeah, I'm a lot more productive. I'm doing things that I never really imagined, and it's kind of

00:14:50.400 --> 00:14:56.559
cool after being a data scientist for maybe ten, it's hard to define how I started, but ten years,

00:14:56.559 --> 00:15:01.840
like, I've had a supercharged year where I'm now doubling my productivity, and that's because of

00:15:01.840 --> 00:15:07.359
LLMs, but also it's because I know that LLMs are imperfect. They have a lot of mistakes, but I can

00:15:07.359 --> 00:15:11.919
now anticipate those mistakes. So with that, I thank you, and we definitely have some time for

00:15:11.919 --> 00:15:17.280
questions, but, yeah, there's my socials. It's just Ryan Timby everywhere, if you're interested.

00:15:17.919 --> 00:15:18.479
But thank you.

